instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system is architected through Model‑Based Systems Engineering (MBSE). Functional and logical layers are captured with SysML, using block definition diagrams to specify component interfaces and internal block diagrams to detail connector relationships. Executable behaviour is modeled in MathWorks Simulink, which can be translated into C++ or Java code for runtime execution. Integration between modelling layers is facilitated by SysML’s extension mechanisms and Simulink’s execution flow, ensuring that component interactions, data flow, and control logic are coordinated across the entire twin. Resource management is handled by the Simulink simulation engine and the generated code, while coordination across subsystems is achieved through the explicit SysML artifact links that define the system’s architecture."
]

instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin development lifecycle follows a sequential abstraction hierarchy—requirements, functional architecture, logical architecture, and product/technical layer—each represented with model‑based systems engineering (MBSE) notations. SysML is typically used at the requirements and functional levels, while architectural description languages such as ACME, AADL, or MontiArc describe component‑connector structures at the logical and product layers. Transition between stages is facilitated by reuse of model artifacts, simulation in MathWorks Simulink or MontiArc Automaton to validate behavior prior to hardware integration, and active components that convert one‑way digital shadow data streams into bidirectional interfaces, thereby enabling governance of design change and stakeholder integration."
]

